content.text:
Found the root cause. Look at `app.js`:

```js
const api = {
  async get(path) {
    const res = await fetch(path);
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(await res.text());
    return res.json();  // ← returns the parsed JSON directly
  },
  async post(path, body) {
    const res = await fetch(path, {
      method: 'POST',
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
      body: JSON.stringify(body),
    });
    if (!res.ok) throw new Error(await res.text());
    return res.json();  // ← returns the parsed JSON directly
  },
};
```

The issue is that `api.get()` and `api.post()` return the parsed JSON directly, but in `checkpoint.js`, the code tries to call `.json()` again on what's already parsed data—treating the returned object as if it were still a Response object. I'm tracing through the API call chain — `ctx.api.get()` already returns the parsed JSON data directly, but `checkpoint.js` is treating it as a Response object and calling `.json()` on it again, which throws a TypeError since arrays don't have that method. Let me check if this pattern is consistent across other views. I'm seeing the same pattern in the form submission handler — `res` is already parsed data, not a Response object, so calling `res.json()` would fail. The `api.post` method throws an error if the response isn't ok, so the catch block would catch that, but on the success path the code is trying to parse something that's already been parsed.

The fix is straightforward: remove the redundant `await res.json()` calls throughout the file. Both GET and POST requests should assign the result directly to a data variable instead of trying to parse it again.

Fixing the API calls... I'm finding the same double-json pattern in two other places in the file: the `renderTopicSelection` and `renderCheckpointForm` functions both call `res.json()` after the API wrapper has already parsed the response. I need to remove those extra `.json()` calls across all three locations so the code directly uses the parsed data.

